# AudioStream — Real-Time Audio Streaming System

A low-latency, distributed audio streaming platform built in C++ for Linux.
Streams live audio between devices over a local network using TCP and UDP sockets.

Think: **mini Sonos streaming pipeline** / **LAN audio broadcaster**.

---

## Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────┐       TCP / UDP        ┌──────────────────────────────────┐
│            SERVER               │  ─────────────────────► │            CLIENT                │
│                                 │                         │                                  │
│  Thread 1: Audio Capture        │                         │  Thread 1: Packet Receiver       │
│  ┌────────────────────────┐     │                         │  ┌─────────────────────────────┐ │
│  │  WAV file OR mic input  │     │                         │  │  recv() → validate seq ID   │ │
│  │  → PCM chunks (20ms)    │     │                         │  └─────────────┬───────────────┘ │
│  └──────────┬─────────────┘     │                         │                │ push            │
│             │ push              │                         │  ┌─────────────▼───────────────┐ │
│  ┌──────────▼─────────────┐     │                         │  │      Jitter Buffer          │ │
│  │   BlockingQueue         │     │                         │  │  Reorder | hold | drain     │ │
│  └──────────┬─────────────┘     │                         │  └─────────────┬───────────────┘ │
│             │ pop               │                         │                │ pop             │
│  Thread 2: Packet Sender        │                         │  Thread 2: Audio Playback        │
│  ┌──────────▼─────────────┐     │                         │  ┌─────────────▼───────────────┐ │
│  │  Packetize + seq IDs    │─────┼──────────────────────►  │  │  PCM → speaker (miniaudio)  │ │
│  │  TCP_NODELAY / UDP      │     │                         │  │  PLC on loss                │ │
│  └─────────────────────────┘    │                         │  └─────────────────────────────┘ │
│                                 │                         │                                  │
│  Metrics / Logger               │                         │  Metrics / Logger                │
└─────────────────────────────────┘                         └──────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Key design decisions

| Concern | Decision | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Inter-thread queue | `BlockingQueue<AudioPacket>` | Sender should sleep when idle; simplicity > lock-free here |
| Packet reordering | `JitterBuffer` (std::map + cv) | O(log n) insert, in-order pop, handles late/lost packets |
| Audio I/O | `miniaudio` (single-header) | Zero dependencies, works on ALSA/PulseAudio/PipeWire |
| Protocol | TCP default, UDP optional | TCP for reliability comparison, UDP to study jitter |
| Loss concealment | Repeat last frame | Simple and effective; Opus PLC replaces this in Phase 2 |
| Latency budget | 20ms chunk + 80ms jitter = ~100ms | Good baseline; tune `--jitter` down for lower latency |

---

## Quick Start

### 1. Setup (first time)

```bash
git clone <your-repo-url> audiostream
cd audiostream
chmod +x setup.sh scripts/*.sh
./setup.sh
```

This will:
- Download `miniaudio.h` (single-header audio library)
- Generate a `test.wav` file (requires `ffmpeg`)
- Configure the CMake build

### 2. Build

```bash
./scripts/build.sh
# or manually:
cmake --build build -j$(nproc)
```

### 3. Run (two terminals)

**Terminal 1 — Server:**
```bash
./build/audiostream_server --source=file:test.wav --loop
```

**Terminal 2 — Client (same machine):**
```bash
./build/audiostream_client --host=127.0.0.1
```

**Over LAN:**
```bash
# On server machine (find its IP with: ip addr)
./build/audiostream_server --source=file:music.wav

# On client machine
./build/audiostream_client --host=192.168.1.42
```

### 4. Quick loopback test

```bash
./scripts/test_local.sh tcp    # TCP test
./scripts/test_local.sh udp    # UDP test
./scripts/test_local.sh tcp 40 # TCP with 40ms jitter buffer
```

---

## Usage Reference

### Server

```
./build/audiostream_server [OPTIONS]

  --source=file:<path>   Stream a WAV file
  --source=mic           Capture from microphone
  --loop                 Loop WAV file (default: on)
  --port=<N>             Data port (default: 9001)
  --proto=tcp|udp        Transport protocol (default: tcp)
  --bind=<addr>          Bind address (default: 0.0.0.0)
  --debug                Enable debug logging
```

### Client

```
./build/audiostream_client [OPTIONS]

  --host=<addr>          Server address (default: 127.0.0.1)
  --port=<N>             Server port (default: 9001)
  --proto=tcp|udp        Transport protocol (default: tcp)
  --jitter=<ms>          Jitter buffer depth in ms (default: 80)
  --debug                Enable debug logging
```

---

## Wire Protocol

Every packet on the wire is:

```
[ PacketHeader (16 bytes) ][ payload (variable) ]

PacketHeader:
  magic[2]        = 0xAD 0xD0
  version         = 0x01
  type            = AUDIO | HANDSHAKE | HEARTBEAT | GOODBYE
  sequence_id     = uint32, monotonically increasing
  timestamp_ms    = uint32, server wall-clock at capture time
  payload_bytes   = uint32, length of following payload
```

Audio payload: raw signed 16-bit PCM, stereo interleaved, 48 kHz.
Each chunk = 960 frames = 20ms of audio.

See `docs/wireshark_filter.md` for Wireshark filters to inspect the traffic live.

---

## Dependencies

| Library | License | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| [miniaudio](https://github.com/mackron/miniaudio) | MIT | Single-header audio I/O. No system deps. |
| pthreads | System | Via CMake `find_package(Threads)` |
| Linux sockets | System | POSIX BSD sockets |

No `apt install` required for audio — miniaudio links directly to ALSA/PipeWire.

---

## Building with Optional Features

### Enable Opus codec (Phase 2)

```bash
sudo apt install libopus-dev
cmake -S . -B build -DUSE_OPUS=ON
cmake --build build -j$(nproc)
```

### Release build (no ASAN, full optimisation)

```bash
cmake -S . -B build-release -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
cmake --build build-release -j$(nproc)
```

### Debug with AddressSanitizer + ThreadSanitizer

The Debug build already enables both. If you hit a TSAN false positive in miniaudio's ring buffer, suppress it:

```bash
TSAN_OPTIONS="suppressions=scripts/tsan_suppress.txt" ./build/audiostream_server ...
```

